@kenlunde Thanks for your reply. Let me try to elaborate it further.

I am aware of the output format of the `mergeFonts` tool. As you know, I am using the source files (CID font resource) of Source Han Sans to build a new font. When there are glyphs that need to be modified to suit my need, I mainly followed [this article](https://blogs.adobe.com/CCJKType/2012/02/simplifying-cidfont-glyph-corrections.html) you wrote, which involves the following steps:

1. Use `tx` to export the glyphs-to-modify from the CID font resource to a .pfa file;
2. Fix them;
3. Merge the fixed glyphs back with `mergeFonts`. This produces a new CID font resource;
4. Use `makeotf` to create a new .otf file.

So far, so good. Then I found I want to remove some glyphs. For instance, the CID font of Source Han Sans language specific version (e.g. `cidfont.ps.OTC.TC`) contains glyphs of all regions for the same codepoint. This is not needed in my use case, so I wanted to keep only those that are actually mapped by the CMap file to save some space. As it is stated that `mergeFonts` is capable of removing glyphs, I thought that it'd be nice to tell `mergeFonts` to skip the glyphs I do not want, so I tried something like this:

```
mergefonts -gx 2946 final_new_cidfont.ps updated_glyphs.ps cidfont.ps.OTC.TC
```

Which doesn't work as I have thought. Swapping `-gx` with `-g` also doesn't make `final_new_cidfont.ps` to only include the glyph with CID 2946, so I should have misinterpreted its use (I have to admit I am not sure what's going on here). Hence my question.

