Replace `py::isinstance<double>` with `py::isinstance<py::float_>` and it's going to work (*). But I'm wondering, why not just use `py::vectorize` directly and let pybind11 do the type checks instead of doing it manually?

(*) Python's `float` is convertible to `double` but it's not necessarily an instance of `double`. Only `py::object`-derived types or a `py::class_` wrapped types are actually instances of a given type, while all others which use `type_caster` are only "convertible to", not "is instance". (Some types also only convertible under certain conditions which makes things more complicated.)

@pybind `py::isinstance` currently returns `false` for all `type_caster` types. I don't think it's correct (or practical) to extend `py::isinstance` to these types, but perhaps an exception might be more appropriate than a simple `false`. Thoughts?

I've found a workaround that seems reasonable, I'm not sure how I might work a solution like no_init into the pybind11 framework though. The issue boils down to the fact that the holder_type for the class is defaulted to unique_ptr, which uses default_delete on the class to create a destructor object. Fortunately, unique_ptr can be overridden with a specific destructor object, so I made a template class and invoked it in my code as follows:

```
template < typename T>
struct BlankDeleter
{
	void operator()(T * inst) const {}
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    pybind11::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");
    pybind11::class_<MyClass, std::unique_ptr<MyClass, BlankDeleter<MyClass>>>(m, "MyClass");
    return m.ptr();
}
```

And now I can set both the constructor and the destructor of the class to be private, and not expose the constructor, and I can have my singleton managed by C++ and accessed in Python.

